<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-411-734  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 411 734.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  July 3 1989 v11 n27 p35(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Race for the Future. (transferring technology from research labsto development teams)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Furger, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Transferring technology from research labs to the market remains akey challenge with which companies continue to struggle.andO;Companies too often fail to tap its employees' new ideas or tocapitalize on their technological innovations.andP;  The technologiesthat usually fail to reach the market are those that do not fitinto the company's existing business strategy.andP;  As a result,scientists start their own businesses to bring their innovationsto market.andP;  The sheer size of a company, and the gaps that existbetween research, development and marketing, can also slow thetransfer of technology.andP;  The best way to circumvent these problemsis to provide a means for effective communication between thesedepartments.andP;  For example, executives from AT and T's research,marketing and sales departments, and the Data Systems Group, meetonce a week to discuss on-going lab projects.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Technology TransferResearch and DevelopmentMarketingIn-HouseCommunicationManagement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>